\name{posteriorPredictive}
\alias{posteriorPredictive}
\title{Check Whether Your Model Actually Fits the Data}
\description{
After fitting a model, a natural question is: "Does this model do a good
job of capturing what's going on in my data?" Posterior predictive checking
answers this by simulating many fake datasets from your fitted model and
comparing them to the real data. If the real data look like a typical
simulated dataset, the model is adequate. If the real data are extreme
(e.g., far more state changes than any simulated dataset), the model is
missing something important.

This function computes several test statistics that capture different aspects
of the data, generates a posterior predictive p-value for each, and produces
a diagnostic plot. The p-values are \strong{not} classical frequentist
p-values — they represent where your observed data fall in the distribution
of simulated data. Values near 0.5 mean your data look typical; values near
0 or 1 mean your data are extreme relative to the model.
}
\usage{
posteriorPredictive(fit, observed_data, nsim = 500,
    test_statistics = c("transitions", "entropy", "consistency",
                        "rate_dispersion", "max_clade_freq"),
    seed = NULL)
}
\arguments{
\item{fit}{A fitted model from \code{\link{fitRateScape}} (class
\code{"ratescapeFit"}).}

\item{observed_data}{A data frame with the same format as the data you used
to fit the model. Row names must match tree tip labels, first column
contains numeric state codes (0-indexed).}

\item{nsim}{Number of posterior predictive simulations. More is better but
slower. 500 (default) is a good balance; use 1000 for publication.}

\item{test_statistics}{Which aspects of the data should be checked? A
character vector containing any combination of:
\describe{
  \item{\code{"transitions"}}{Number of state changes implied by parsimony
    (Fitch algorithm). Checks whether the model produces the right amount
    of evolutionary change.}
  \item{\code{"entropy"}}{Shannon entropy of tip state frequencies. Checks
    whether the model produces realistic state diversity. If your data are
    heavily skewed toward one state, entropy will be low.}
  \item{\code{"consistency"}}{Retention index — measures how well character
    states match the tree structure. High values mean states are
    phylogenetically conserved (clustered on the tree).}
  \item{\code{"rate_dispersion"}}{Variance of per-edge change indicators.
    High dispersion means changes are concentrated on a few branches
    rather than spread evenly.}
  \item{\code{"max_clade_freq"}}{Maximum state frequency within the largest
    clade. Detects whether the model captures large-scale phylogenetic
    structure in the character.}
}
Default uses all five statistics, which is recommended.}

\item{seed}{Optional integer for reproducibility.}
}
